  "faq": [
    {
      "question": "What is the difference between Full Account and S2F?",
      "answer": "Full Account requires passing an evaluation phase with profit targets and drawdown limits. S2F (Straight-to-Funded) allows you to start trading with real money immediately without an evaluation phase.",
      "source": "https://help.daytraders.com/en/articles/11583644-s2f-straight-to-sim-funded"
    },
    {
      "question": "How do payouts work?",
      "answer": "Payouts are available after 8-10 trading days with minimum profit requirements. You keep 100% of profits with no split to Day Traders. Maximum payouts range from $1,000 to $5,000 depending on account size.",
      "source": "https://help.daytraders.com/en/articles/11583644-s2f-straight-to-sim-funded"
    },
    {
      "question": "What is the consistency rule?",
      "answer": "The consistency rule requires you to maintain profitable trading days. For S2F accounts, you need to maintain 20% consistency, while Full Account requires 30% consistency.",
      "source": "https://help.daytraders.com/en/articles/9917782-consistency-rule"
    },
    {
      "question": "Is there an activation fee?",
      "answer": "Full Account has a $130 activation fee, while S2F accounts have no activation fees. You only pay the one-time evaluation fee for Full Account or the one-time fee for S2F.",
      "source": "https://help.daytraders.com/en/articles/11583644-s2f-straight-to-sim-funded"
    },
    {
      "question": "What happens if I hit the drawdown limit?",
      "answer": "If you hit the maximum drawdown limit, your account will be reset. For Full Account, you can restart the evaluation. For S2F, you would need to purchase a new account.",
      "source": "https://help.daytraders.com/en/articles/11583644-s2f-straight-to-sim-funded"
    },
    {
      "question": "Can I trade during news events?",
      "answer": "Yes, news trading is permitted in both evaluation and funded phases. DayTraders allows news trading but advises traders to exercise caution due to increased volatility during news events.",
      "source": "https://help.daytraders.com/en/articles/9855087-evaluation-account-rules"
    },
